Oh, certainly not &quot;no interest&quot;.  I got very interested, but then I got 
excited about the idea of tagging tests with ids of items in a bug 
database, a la

http://www.developertesting.com/archives/month200608/20060811-FailingTests.html

This is more appealing to me--tests that stay ignored for any length of 
time tend to have some sort of metadata in an issue tracker about them.  
This also allows an interesting workflow: I see a problem with the code, 
but for some reason, you&#39;re the right one to fix it, and you&#39;re ( on 
vacation | busy doing something else | mad at me ).  I can open a bug in 
bugzilla, and then check in a test with @Ignore(untilBugFixed=&quot;12345&quot;).

This means that there&#39;s a more general idea of @Ignore(if) that I need 
to get my head around.  And before that, I really want to get the custom 
runner architecture in better shape, so that you could have built this 
easily yourself.  And before that, there&#39;s settling into a new job, 
which will eventually provide more time and energy to work on JUnit.

So, interested, but distracted...

    David Saff

